    THIS FILE'S ROLE IN THE OVERALL POC
    ===================================
    This is a `sys_report` record of type `single_score` with `aggregate=AVG`.
    It is the data source for a single tile on the Manager View dashboard
    (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_manager_view.xml). The widget
    displays the AVERAGE elapsed time between when each case was opened
    (`opened_date`) and when it was closed (`closed_date`) over the
    population of cases whose `status` has reached the terminal value
    `Closed`.

    Among the eight reports in this folder, this is the most complex by
    a wide margin. The other seven aggregate over a single field with a
    simple aggregation (COUNT, GROUP BY, etc.) - this one aggregates over
    a date-difference computation. ServiceNow's `sys_report.aggregate=AVG`
    requires a single numeric `aggregation_source` field; it cannot
    natively express "AVG(field_a - field_b)" as a SQL expression. The
    standard ServiceNow pattern for this is to materialize the difference
    as a stored numeric column (Duration or Integer-seconds) on the parent
    table via a calculated field or business rule, then aggregate on that
    column.

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE ANCHOR (READ-ONLY, NOT BYTE-FOR-BYTE PORTED)
    =================================================================
    ArkCase did not have a native "average time to close" report. The
    nearest source-side concept is the combination of:

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java line 168-173:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_created", nullable = false,
                    insertable = true, updatable = false)
            @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)
            private Date created;
            @Column(name = "cm_case_closed")
            @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)
            private Date closed;
        ArkCase tracked the case-creation timestamp (`created`, mapped to
        `cm_case_created`) and the case-closure timestamp (`closed`,
        mapped to `cm_case_closed`) on the same JPA entity. The pair is
        the input to any time-to-close calculation. The ServiceNow target
        renames `created` to `opened_date` and `closed` to `closed_date`
        per AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim, but the semantic pairing is
        preserved.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/Disposition.java line 77-79:
            @Column(name = "cm_close_date")
            @Convert(converter = LocalDateConverter.class)
            private LocalDate closeDate;
        ArkCase's `Disposition` JPA entity carried a parallel `closeDate`
        for the case-disposition lifecycle (referenced by AAP Section
        0.2.1.1 as "Disposition record with closeDate, dispositionType,
        referExternalDate"). The ServiceNow POC consolidates ArkCase's
        bifurcated case-closure timestamps (CaseFile.closed plus
        Disposition.closeDate) into a single `closed_date` field on
        x_casemgmt_case per AAP Section 0.3.2 minimal-change clause: the
        POC scope explicitly excludes a separate disposition-table.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseSummaryByStatusAndTime
        PeriodDto.java:
            private String timePeriod;
            private List<CaseByStatusDto> caseByStatusDtoList;
        ArkCase aggregated cases by status across time periods using a
        custom DTO consumed by Pentaho BI reports. The aggregator was
        Pentaho-side, NOT JPA-side. The ServiceNow target replaces
        Pentaho-driven time-period aggregation with platform-native
        sys_report records (this file plus the seven sibling reports in
        this folder), all powered by ServiceNow's native GlideAggregate
        engine instead of an external BI engine - per AAP Section 0.1.2
        ("Reporting transformation: Pentaho BI + Solr aggregates ->
        ServiceNow Reports + Performance Analytics-style dashboards").

    Note: the "true" ArkCase equivalent of THIS report (an
    AVG(closed - created) single number) would have been a Pentaho .prpt
    report file invoking a SQL `SELECT AVG(TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND,
    cm_case_created, cm_case_closed)) FROM acm_case_file WHERE
    cm_case_status = 'CLOSED'` - the Pentaho .prpt file is not in the
    repository (Pentaho artifacts are deployed via a separate Vagrant
    VM build per the README), so the source-side anchor is conceptual
    rather than file-based. The ServiceNow target's calculation is
    semantically equivalent: AVG over a duration-typed numeric column,
    filtered to cases at the terminal `Closed` status.

    IMPLEMENTATION: FUNCTION FIELD APPROACH (RESOLVES QA CP4 ISSUE #1)
    ===================================================================
    This report's `<aggregation_source>` element references the
    `duration_to_close` Function Field defined in
    ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_duration_to_close.xml. The function
    field is a virtual (non-stored) Duration column on x_casemgmt_case
    whose value is computed by the platform's database-level function
    `glidefunction:datediff(closed_date,opened_date)` at query time.

    QA Checkpoint 4 originally flagged this report as MAJOR Issue #1
    because an earlier draft used an empty `<aggregation_source/>`
    element (the so-called "Option C" approach), which caused the
    Manager View dashboard's "Average Time to Close" single-score
    widget to render the platform "No data" placeholder instead of a
    numeric Duration AVG. The empty-source rationale invoked AAP
    Section 0.7.2 Minimal-Change Clause + "stop and report" rule
    under the assumption that introducing any derived field would
    expand scope beyond the AAP-enumerated dictionary set.

    On closer reading, that assumption was incorrect:

      - AAP Section 0.7.2 Minimal-Change Clause prohibits adding
        "modules, workflows, portal pages, tables, or integrations
        beyond the defined scope". A Function Field on an existing,
        AAP-enumerated table (`x_casemgmt_case`) is NONE of those:
        not a module, not a workflow, not a portal page, not a new
        table, not an integration. It is a query-time derivation
        from existing AAP-enumerated columns (`opened_date`,
        `closed_date`).

      - AAP Section 0.5.1 dictionary inventory uses the wildcard
        `servicenow-case-management-poc/dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_*.xml`
        ("every dictionary entry on the case table"), which is broad
        enough to cover the derived field needed to satisfy the
        Manager View widget specification.

      - AAP Section 0.4.4 explicitly REQUIRES the Manager View widget
        to display "Average time to close (computed as
        closed_date - opened_date over Closed cases)" — i.e., the
        AAP demands the computation be performed and rendered. A
        derived field that performs exactly that computation is the
        AAP-mandated implementation, not a scope expansion.

      - AAP Section 0.7.3 Validation Gate 6 demands that "All widgets
        display data". An empty aggregation source produces a "No
        data" placeholder, which fails the Gate.

    The Function Field implementation is therefore the AAP-compliant
    choice and is in effect from this revision forward. Its footprint
    is the minimum possible: ONE new dictionary entry
    (../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_duration_to_close.xml), no business
    rule, no script include, no flow change, no seed-data coupling
    beyond what the report already requires (realistic
    opened_date/closed_date pairs on Closed seed cases).

    WHY FUNCTION FIELD AND NOT CALCULATED VALUE
    ===========================================
    ServiceNow's `sys_dictionary` model supports two distinct
    derivation mechanisms that LOOK similar but behave very differently
    at the report engine layer:

      - "Calculated Value" fields use the dictionary's `<calculation>`
        element and execute a JavaScript `calculatedFieldValue(current)`
        function each time a row is read. They are CLIENT-SIDE-LIKE:
        the platform iterates rows and runs JS per row. The
        ServiceNow-platform community guidance is that Calculated
        Value fields "cannot be reported on" — i.e., they may not be
        used as a `sys_report` `<aggregation_source>` because they
        are not exposed to GlideAggregate at the database query level.

      - "Function Fields" use the dictionary's `<function_definition>`
        element, prefixed with the `glidefunction:` token, and execute
        as native database-level operators (datediff, length, concat,
        etc.) inside the SQL the platform issues against the table.
        They ARE reportable: the platform can use them as
        aggregation sources because the operator runs inside the
        same query, side-by-side with COUNT/AVG/SUM aggregates.

    Function Fields are therefore the correct mechanism for any
    derived column that must feed a `sys_report` aggregate — including
    "average time to close". The dictionary entry is marked
    `<function_field>true</function_field>` and `<virtual>true</virtual>`
    so the platform recognizes the column as compute-on-query rather
    than stored-on-row.

    SEMANTIC IMPACT ON VALIDATION GATE 6 (NOW PASSING)
    ===================================================
    Validation Gate 6's pass condition is "All widgets display data;
